{"ts":"2026-06-27T15:48:06.632Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Initiating Ticket Integration**\n\nI'm starting the integration of the support page with the backend ticket APIs. My plan involves defining an `async` function, `fetchTickets`, to retrieve data from `/api/v1/support`. Authentication will be standard.\n\n\n**Mapping Priority Logic**\n\nI'm now focusing on mapping backend priority levels (\"P1\", \"P2\", \"P3\") to frontend UI styles (\"critical\", \"high\", \"medium\"). I've decided to enhance the `getPriorityStyle` function to accommodate both sets of values for increased robustness. I'll need to update the UI to allow both models to be supported.\n\n\n**Refining Priority & Status**\n\nI've significantly refined the priority and status mapping. The `getPriorityStyle` function is now fully robust, accepting both backend (\"P1\", \"P2\", \"P3\") and frontend (\"critical\", \"high\", \"medium\") values, and I'm very happy with how it's looking. Now, I've written a small helper function, `normalizeTicket`, to handle backend/frontend status mappings. I'll transform \"OPEN\", \"INVESTIGATING\", \"RESOLVED\" to \"open\", \"in_progress\", \"resolved\" for UI consistency.\n\n\n**Finalizing Ticket Data Transformation**\n\nI've crafted a comprehensive `normalizeTicket` function, and I'm really pleased with it. It meticulously maps and standardizes the ticket data received from the backend API. It handles status transformations from \"OPEN\", \"IN_PROGRESS\", \"INVESTIGATING\", and \"RESOLVED\" to \"open\", \"in_progress\", and \"resolved\", respectively. I'm confident it ensures perfect consistency for the UI, with complete confidence now that all data formats are supported. This has been a key step in ensuring data integrity. I feel like it's a huge victory.\n\n\n**Implementing Ticket Creation Flow**\n\nI'm now integrating the ticket creation process. I'm using an existing loading state for the request, dynamically updating logs with success or failure messages. On success, I'll add a success log, show a toast, clear the form, and set the `selectedTicketId` to the newly created ticket. On failure, I'll update the logs to show the error and allow retries, making it look premium.\n\n\n**Connecting Reply Logic**\n\nI'm now integrating the reply functionality to ensure seamless backend interaction. I've set up the necessary API call using the real backend comment endpoint, `/api/v1/support/${selectedTicketId}`, with the right method and headers. If it's successful, it updates the ticket data, which will be merged into my `tickets` state, which is quite clean. I'm taking another look at the page component lines 1-74, and re-reading the states.\n\n\n"}}
